05786nam a22010215i 9780691213057DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20211994nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912130577 a10.1515/97806912130572doi  a(DE-B1597)554829  a(OCoLC)1257324274  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJC327b.S65 1994eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.1/52221 aSpruyt, Hendrik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Sovereign State and Its Competitors :bAn Analysis of Systems Change /cHendrik Spruyt. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b4 maps 9 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in International History and Politics ;v17600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF MAPS AND TABLES -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I: CONTINGENCY, CHOICE, AND CONSTRAINT -- tCHAPTER 1 Structural Change in International Relations -- tCHAPTER 2 Organizational Variation and Selection in the International System -- tCHAPTER 3 Modes of Nonterritorial Organization: Feudalism, the Church, and the Holy Roman Empire -- tPART II: THE EMERGENCE OF NEW MODES OF ORGANIZATION -- tCHAPTER 4 The Economic Renaissance of the Late Middle Ages -- tCHAPTER 5 The Rise of the Sovereign, Territorial State in Capetian France -- tCHAPTER 6 The Fragmentation of the German Empire and the Rise of the Hanseatic League -- tCHAPTER 7 The Development of the Italian City-states -- tPART III: COMPETITION, MUTUAL EMPOWERMENT, AND CHOICE: THE ADVANTAGES OF SOVEREIGN TERRITORIALITY -- tCHAPTER 8 The Victory of the Sovereign State -- tPART IV: CONCLUSION -- tCHAPTER 9 Character, Tempo, and Prospects for Change in the International System -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe present international system, composed for the most part of sovereign, territorial states, is often viewed as the inevitable outcome of historical development. Hendrik Spruyt argues that there was nothing inevitable about the rise of the state system, however. Examining the competing institutions that arose during the decline of feudalism--among them urban leagues, independent communes, city states, and sovereign monarchies--Spruyt disposes of the familiar claim that the superior size and war-making ability of the sovereign nation-state made it the natural successor to the feudal system. The author argues that feudalism did not give way to any single successor institution in simple linear fashion. Instead, individuals created a variety of institutional forms, such as the sovereign, territorial state in France, the Hanseatic League, and the Italian city-states, in reaction to a dramatic change in the medieval economic environment. Only in a subsequent selective phase of institutional evolution did sovereign, territorial authority prove to have significant institutional advantages over its rivals. Sovereign authority proved to be more successful in organizing domestic society and structuring external affairs. Spruyt's interdisciplinary approach not only has important implications for change in the state system in our time, but also presents a novel analysis of the general dynamics of institutional change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSovereigntyxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aBean, Richard.  aCarolingian Empire.  aFlorence.  aGenoa.  aGuelph.  aHamburg.  aHohenstaufen.  aInterregnum.  aKontor.  aNorth, Douglass.  aOtto III.  aPodesta.  aRice, Eugene.  aRoman law.  aSignoria.  aTeutonic Order.  aValois Dynasty.  aVenice.  aWaltz, Kenneth.  aWelf.  aZupko, Ronald.  acanon law.